Rating: 4
Served this for a dinner for 12 and used fresh seabass it was delicious. I did add ground pine nuts and lemon zest to the crust and used panko crumbs as others suggested. The fish took a little longer to cook as it was quite thick but it was buttery and very delicious. The people that bought this dinner from our charity could not stop talking about how good the fish was! Make this it is worth it. I don't like cooking fish for a dinner party but would do this over again in a heartbeat!

Rating: 4
This was so good that I am still thinking about it the next morning. Made it exactly as written but did thin the coulis just a bit with lemon juice and a tiny bit of stock. The cooking time was just right. This would be a terrific dinner for guests, since it goes together quickly and a lot can be done ahead of time. Served with parslied new potatoes and frisee salad with bacon and asparagus (from this site).

Rating: 4
I made this last night using Pacific Red Snapper which is more thin than halibut and therefore cooks more rapidly. Otherwise, I followed the recipe exactly and wouldn't change it one bit. I like well seasoned food and found the coulis was just right. More hefty flavor would overpower the fish. This could all be made ahead for company, not just the bread crumbs and coulis. The fish would be laid out on a baking dish, covered by the mayo/mustard combo and then the bread crumbs. This could be put in the frig for a while, at least an hour or so, and thrown into the oven 20 minutes before dinner is served. I'll make this over and over again!

